04326nam a22007335i 9780691186306DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911863067 a10.1515/97806911863062doi  a(DE-B1597)501623  a(OCoLC)1076462587  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPR9387.4b.G75 2000 7aLIT0040102bisacsh04a8232231 aGriswold, Wendy, eauthor.10aBearing Witness :bReaders, Writers, and the Novel in Nigeria /cWendy Griswold. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Cultural Sociology ;v600tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF FIGURES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tKEY DATES IN NIGERIAN HISTORY -- tCHAPTER 1. To Understand the Novel in Nigeria -- tCHAPTER 2. The Nigerian Fiction Complex -- tCHAPTER 3. Nigerian Novels -- tCHAPTER 4. Capturing the Past and Inventing the Future -- tAPPENDIX A. Nigerian novels -- tAPPENDIX B. Nigerian authors -- tAPPENDIX C. Coding forms -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX  aGreed, frustrated love, traffic jams, infertility, politics, polygamy. These--together with depictions of traditional village life and the impact of colonialism made familiar to Western readers through Chinua Achebe's writing--are the stuff of Nigerian fiction. Bearing Witness examines this varied content and the determined people who, against all odds, write, publish, sell, and read novels in Africa's most populous nation. Drawing on interviews with Nigeria's writers, publishers, booksellers, and readers, surveys, and a careful reading of close to 500 Nigerian novels--from lightweight romances to literary masterpieces--Wendy Griswold explores how global cultural flows and local conflicts meet in the production and reception of fiction. She argues that Nigerian readers and writers form a reading class that unabashedly believes in progress, rationality, and the slow-but-inevitable rise of a reading culture. But they do so within a society that does not support their assumptions and does not trust literature, making them modernists in a country that is simultaneously premodern and postmodern. Without privacy, reliable electricity, political freedom, or even social toleration of bookworms, these Nigerians write and read political satires, formula romances, war stories, complex gender fiction, blood-and-sex crime capers, nostalgic portraits of village life, and profound explorations of how decent people get by amid urban chaos. Bearing Witness is an inventive and moving work of cultural sociology that may be the most comprehensive sociological analysis of a literary system ever written.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aAuthors and readerszNigeria. 0aFictionxAppreciationzNigeria. 0aLiterature and societyzNigeria. 0aNigerian fiction (English)xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / African.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691186306zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691186306.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN